definition.value: Anatomical part of a plant, such as fruit, seed, pod, leaf, stem or flower as well as the whole plant.

label.value: whole, shape achieved by forming, thickness 1.5-7 cm.
physical state, shape or form, multiple

definition.value: The physical state of the food product (liquid, semiliquid, semisolid, or solid). Solid food products are further subdivided by shape or form. Terms are provided for products that have both liquid and solid components or that incorporate air or other gases. [FDA CFSAN 1995]

label.value: divided into pieces, thickness more than 1.5 cm.

definition.value: Refers to natural or formed shape as appropriate, regardless of size, which may vary from very large (e.g., beef carcass) to very small (e.g., poppy seed, yeast cell).

label.value: divided into halves, quarters or segments

definition.value: Divided into pieces whose shape is defined in relation to the shape of the whole, i.e., halves, quarters, or segments. It is used regardless of the size of the whole.

label.value: whole, shape achieved by forming, thickness 0.3-1.5 cm.
whole, shape achieved by forming, thickness bigger than 7 cm.

definition.value: Divided into pieces whose shape bears little or no relation to the shape of the whole. If all dimensions are below 0.2 cm., use *DISINTEGRATED OR GROUND*. Examples are: bread slice, cubed beef, sliced carrot, cut green beans, apple ring, shredded cabbage or cheese.

label.value: whole, shape achieved by forming, thickness <0.3 cm.

definition.value: Used to broadly characterize a food product based on the extent of heat applied. Heat treatment affects the flavor and textural characteristics of a food and thus consumer preparation time. Heat treatment causes chemical changes and/or reduction of enzyme and of microbial activity and thus affects food safety and shelflife. Specifics of preparation are covered by *G. COOKING METHOD* and *H. TREATMENT APPLIED*. [FDA CFSAN 1995]

label.value: heat-treated, multiple components, different degrees of treatment

definition.value: Cooked at moderate to high levels of heat in which no liquid is added and only small amounts of fat may be added to prevent sticking.
Cooked without moisture, covered or uncovered, in an oven.
Cooked without moisture under or over intense direct heat.
Cooked without moisture over direct heat from a charcoal fire.
Cooking on a flat surface at medium heat with only a sufficient amount of fat used to prevent sticking.
Cooking by agitating the food over a dry, high heat source, resulting in exploding.
Cooking with direct heat until the surface of the food is browned, usually associated with bread or sandwiches.
Cooking in varying amounts of water, water-based liquid or steam.

label.value: cooking in water or water-based liquid

definition.value: Cooked in boiling water at 100 degrees C (212 degrees F).
Cooked in boiling water at 212 degrees F.; water that is not absorbed into the food product is discarded after cooking.

label.value: boiling in large amount of liquid

definition.value: Cooked in boiling water at 212 degrees F. Liquid to solid ratio is greater than 2:1.

label.value: boiling in small amount of liquid
